Time dependent Cox

J.S. González-Martínez

2021-09-03

Below are the results for the second series of Cox proportional hazard analyses. The analyses below treat covariates as time-dependent. We developed univariate and multivariate models.
Libraries required 
library(readr)
library(tidyverse)
library(lubridate)
library(plyr)
library(dplyr)
library(survival)
library(survminer)
Upload data 
all_df <- read.csv("all_merged.csv")

all_df <- all_df[,-1]
Further data processing: Calculate time intervals required for analyses 
#verify no observations have a time of observation greater than overall time of survival 
nrow(filter(all_df, time_survob > time_surv))
## [1] 0
#reorder df so time intervals are ordered by ID and time_survob is ordered in descending order within ID clusters

all_df <- all_df[with(all_df, order(brc_id, -time_survob)),]

#calculate time 1

all_df <- all_df %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(time1 = time_surv - time_survob) 

#reorder df so time intervals are ordered by ID and time1 is ordered in ascending order within ID clusters

all_df <- all_df[with(all_df, order(brc_id, time1)),]

#calculate time2

all_df <- all_df %>% 
  group_by(brc_id) %>% 
  mutate(time2 = lead(time1, default = 0))

#screen observations where time1 > time 2 - which will need to be removed because the model will see them as illogical

compare0 <- filter(all_df, time1 > time2) %>% 
  dplyr::select(brc_id, obsv_id, min_dateobsv, max_dateobsv, date_entry, time_surv, time_survob, time1, time2)

head(compare0, 10)[,-1:-2] #index printing so patient IDs are not printed and time2 shows in html file

#develop a function to obtain quick frequency tables percentages

freq_per_info <- function(var) {#function to generate a table with frequencies and percentages
  library(epiDisplay) #library required 
  tab1(var, 
       sort.group = "decreasing",
       cum.percentage = T,
       graph = F)}

Analysis
Establish death event rules

Censor data based on time intervals

Rules:

  1. Check the last time interval per patient (i.e., when time_surv = time 2)

  2. If there is a date of death recorded for that patient, and that date of death was before the cohort’s end span (“2019-05-01”), then the interval corresponds to a death within the study period

  3. All other observations shall be censored

all_df <- all_df %>% 
   dplyr::mutate(event_death = ifelse((time_surv == time2) & !is.na(Date_Of_Death) & 
                                      (Date_Of_Death  <= "2019-05-01"), 1, 0)) %>% 
   dplyr::mutate(event_death = as.numeric(event_death))

table(all_df$event_death)
## 
##     0     1 
## 53828  5145
Univariate models

Functionalise graph plotting

#function to customise plot of Schoenfeld's test results

plot_schoenfeld <- function(resx, var_name) {
  my_plot0 <- ggcoxzph(resx, 
                       title = print(paste("Schoenfeld's test results for", var_name)),
                       xlab = "Time (days)", 
                       ylab = print(paste("Beta(t) for", var_name)))
    
  return(my_plot0)}

#function to customise plots of survival curves (only works for continuous variables)

plot_surv <- function(fitobj, var_name, namesobj) { 
 my_plot1 <- ggsurvplot(fitobj, #default
           palette = "nejm", #default
           censor.size = 2, #default
           title = print("Survival probablity in OxNHS dementia patients"),
           subtitle = print(paste("Adjusted for", var_name, "(time-dependent analysis)")),
           font.subtitle = c(14, "italic"),
           xlab = "Time (days)", #default
           legend.title = str_to_title(var_name),
           legend.labs = namesobj)
    
  return(my_plot1)}

We plotted models’ results as forest plots for models that met the proportionality assumption and for which all covariates were significant.

Forest plot

#the steps below apply to all forest plots created henceforward

#subset data for forest plot's aesthetics 

forest_df1 <- all_df %>% 
  transmute(time1, #extract survival object terms
            time2, 
            event_death,
            Gender = factor(Gender_Value), #extract covariates of interest and rename
            `Age (observation)` = age_obsv) %>% 
  mutate(Gender = relevel(Gender, ref = "Female")) #relevel when necessary so hazard ratios use consistent reference groups

#fit model again, but use new variable names for aesthetics purposes

new1 <- coxph(Surv(time1, time2, event_death) ~ Gender + `Age (observation)`, data = forest_df1)

#print forest plot

ggforest(new1,
         cpositions = c(0.003, 0.17, 0.4)) #cpositions controls positions of text in plot
